<LegalLayout
  title="Record Your Service"
  description="Three board-agnostic ways to get a real service recording into Sound Buddy — USB stick, laptop DAW, or your livestream's audio track."
  updated="July 11, 2026"
  eyebrow="Guide"
>
  <p>
    The demo report card shows you what Sound Buddy can do. Grading your own service just means
    getting a recording of it onto your Mac — and you almost certainly already have a way to do
    that. Here are three options, roughly in order of how little extra gear they need.
  </p>

  <h2>1. Record to a USB stick on your console/mixer</h2>
  <p>
    Most digital mixers — from a basic USB recorder up through a full-size digital console — can
    record the main mix, or every individual channel, straight to a USB drive plugged into the
    board. This is usually the simplest option because there's nothing extra to bring.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Plug a USB drive into your console before the service starts.</li>
    <li>Start the recording from the console's built-in recorder before you begin, and stop it
      once you're done.</li>
    <li>Move the file from the USB drive onto your Mac, then open it with Sound Buddy.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Exact steps vary by console — check your board's manual for where the USB recorder lives and
    which format it saves in (WAV is ideal; most consoles default to it).
  </p>

  <h2>2. Capture on a laptop with a DAW or audio interface</h2>
  <p>
    If your console has a laptop nearby (for a live-stream mix, playback tracks, or multitrack
    recording), you can capture the service directly into recording software instead.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Connect the board's main output — or a dedicated recording send — into your laptop,
      either via a USB connection the console already offers or a separate audio interface.</li>
    <li>Open any DAW (Logic, Ableton, Reaper, or a free option like Audacity) and start a new
      recording before the service begins.</li>
    <li>Export the take as a WAV or AIFF file when you're done, then analyze it in Sound Buddy.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This route takes a little more setup than a USB stick, but gives you a file you can also use
    for other purposes (like a livestream mix) at the same time.
  </p>

  <h2>3. Pull the audio from your livestream recording</h2>
  <p>
    If your church already streams or records the service to video, you don't need a separate
    audio capture at all — the audio is already sitting inside that video file.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Locate the recorded service video (from your streaming software, camera, or platform
      export).</li>
    <li>Extract just the audio track using your video software's export options, or a simple
      audio-extraction tool.</li>
    <li>Save the extracted audio as a WAV, AIFF, or MP3 file and open it in Sound Buddy.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This is the lowest-effort option if a recording already exists — no extra hardware, no extra
    step during the service itself.
  </p>

  <h2>A note on console-specific steps</h2>
  <p>
    Every board is a little different, and walking through button-by-button steps for every make
    and model is out of scope here. If you get stuck, your console's manual is the best first stop,
    followed by the manufacturer's support site or community forums for your specific model.
  </p>
</LegalLayout>
